      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "1. Overview"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "The stored procedure "
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "usp_SSIS_CreateSeptsCsvExtract",
          "marks": [
            {
              "type": "code"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " is designed to execute an SSIS (SQL Server Integration Services) package that extracts data into a CSV format. The procedure dynamically constructs a command to run the SSIS package using "
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "dtexec",
          "marks": [
            {
              "type": "code"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": ", a command-line utility for executing SSIS packages. The procedure sets specific variables within the SSIS package to the current database name and server name, ensuring the package runs with the correct context."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "attrs": {
        "level": 1
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "2. Complexity Level: Medium"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "The complexity of this stored procedure is considered medium. While the logic itself is straightforward, involving the execution of an external SSIS package, it requires understanding of both SQL Server stored procedures and SSIS package execution. Additionally, it involves enabling and using "
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "xp_cmdshell",
          "marks": [
            {
              "type": "code"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": ", which adds a layer of complexity due to security considerations."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
